(on top of the expected  behavior).
Consequently, in the spatial current density ,
the non-linear  contribution is  suppressed relative
to the linear  term.
Exactly the same conclusion holds for the terms
quadratic in flow velocity in the stress tensor ()
as compared to the linear terms involving the gradient of the velocity.






Supersymmetric Hydrodynamics 

We now wish to generalize the preceding
discussion of hydrodynamic fluctuations 
to the case of supersymmetric theories.
For ease of presentation,
in this section we consider theories with 
supersymmetry in four dimensions.
Such theories possess a set of conserved supercurrents,
which we will denote by
 and ,
which are Lorentz vector-spinors.
The corresponding conserved supercharges satisfy
the supersymmetry algebra,
(
    We follow the notations
    of Wess and Bagger for spinors.
    In particular, undotted early Greek indices ...
    label  two-component Weyl spinors,
    while corresponding dotted indices label 
    conjugate Weyl spinors.
    These indices are raised or lowered using the antisymmetric tensor
    


,
    so that
    


    and
    


.
    Extended Pauli matrices are
    
    and , 
    and the spinor representation generators of the Lorentz group are
    





    and
    




.
    ) 
 

The theory may also have a chiral
 symmetry (-symmetry), whose charge  does not
commute with the supercharges, 
 
as well as various additional internal
symmetries whose charges  do commute with the supercharges.
For definiteness, we will assume that the theory does have -symmetry,
and that this symmetry is not spontaneously broken.
    
    In  supersymmetry, conservation of the  -symmetry
    current requires scale invariance.
    Non-scale invariant theories will have anomalies in the -symmetry
    current, although it is often then possible to combine the anomalous
    -symmetry with an anomalous chiral symmetry to yield a non-anomalous
    -symmetry.
    If there is no non-anomalous -symmetry,
    then the -charge density will not be a
    hydrodynamic degree of freedom
    
    
    
    
    
    For such theories, just ignore all mention of the -symmetry
    current in the following discussion.
     

Since the supercurrents are conserved, one might expect that
fluctuations in supercharge densities will be unable to relax locally,
just as ordinary current conservation directly leads to diffusive
relaxation of bosonic conserved charge densities.
And slow relaxation of supercharge densities may in turn generate
long-time tails in bosonic  observables which can couple
quadratically to supercharge densities.
In other words, even though supercharge densities are fermionic operators
with vanishing expectation value in any conventional statistical ensemble,
the dynamics of supercharge fluctuations may produce distinctive effects
in ordinary bosonic observables.
We will see that these expectations are largely correct.




Supercharge fluctuations 

The hydrodynamic nature of supercharge densities is
reflected in the long-time behavior of the corresponding
correlation function,
 
Finite-temperature thermal ensembles are not invariant under
supersymmetry transformations.
    
    Formally, the transformation of a statistical density matrix 
    under any infinitesimal symmetry transformation is defined 
    by the condition that
    



