 Supersymmetric long-time tails 

As in the non-supersymmetric case, second order
terms in the constitutive relations are sufficient to understand
the leading long-time tails in  correlators of all conserved currents.
Proceeding in exactly the same way as in
Section ,
one sees from the absence of any  term
in the stress tensor constitutive relation ()
that supercharge density fluctuations
have no effect on the leading long-time tail in the stress-stress correlator.
Consequently, the stress-stress correlator
has the same form as in the non-supersymmetric case
[i.e. , Eq. () for scale-invariant theories,
or Eq. () for the general case]
provided the -charge is included as one of the global bosonic charges.
Similarly, the leading long-time tails () in correlators
of ordinary bosonic symmetry currents
are unaffected by the presence of supercharge density fluctuations.

In contrast,
the presence of a quadratic supercharge density term in the
constitutive relation () for the -symmetry current
means that the long time tail in the -symmetry current correlator
is affected by supercharge fluctuations.
One finds that the leading large time behavior is

 

If the same analysis is applied to the
spatial supercurrent correlation function,
one finds that the second order  terms in
the constitutive relation () do not generate long-time tails.
Because the speed of ordinary sound ()
and supersound () differ,
fluctuations (with the same wavevector)
in momentum density and supercharge density
cannot remain in phase.
This is analogous to the fact that only transverse momentum
density fluctuations, not longitudinal sound waves,
contribute to the long-time tail () of
ordinary current-current correlators.
So the supercurrent correlator
,
at ,
should decay exponentially in time.
    
    Because , one finds that higher-order 
    terms in the supercurrent constitutive relation
    also do not generate (higher-order) power-law tails.
     

The differing long-time behaviors of the stress tensor
and supercurrent correlators does not
conflict with the fact that the stress-energy tensor
and supercurrents belong to the same supersymmetry multiplet.
The supersymmetry algebra implies simple
relations between  inserted thermal correlation
functions of conserved currents, but not between
conventional thermal correlation functions, for the reasons
noted in footnote .





Long-time tails in  supersymmetric
Yang-Mills theory 

As a specific application, the above discussion (trivially generalized)
may be applied to  supersymmetric  Yang-Mills theory,
at the origin of the moduli space and at non-zero temperature.
    
    The vacuum degeneracy associated with a non-trivial moduli space
    is lifted at non-zero temperature.
    For sufficiently high temperatures, the only stable equilibrium
    states lie at the origin of moduli space.
     
Once again,
hydrodynamic degrees of freedom are densities of conserved charges.
In  supersymmetric Yang-Mills theory,
