depend on the values of the
equilibrium energy density ,
the -charge susceptibility ,
the shear viscosity , and -charge diffusion constant .
These parameters must be
treated as input from short-distance physics.
In a weakly coupled theory,
these quantities can be computed in perturbation theory,
but no field-theoretic calculation is available
when the coupling constant is large.
However, the AdS/CFT correspondence predicts specific
values for these parameters in 
supersymmetric Yang-Mills theory in the
limit of large  and large 't Hooft coupling.
The equilibrium
energy density is evaluated from the thermodynamics of the dual
Anti-de Sitter black hole, and is
predicted to be
 
The shear viscosity is evaluated as the zero-frequency limit of
the absorption cross-section of gravitons by the black three-brane
(with gravitons polarized parallel to the brane),
and is predicted to be

 
Hence, in this limit
the ratio 
is predicted to equal .

The diffusion constant and susceptibility for  charges are extracted from the
pole structure of the thermal correlation function of 
charge densities, and are predicted to be
 
The supercharge diffusion constant  has, to our knowledge,
not yet been evaluated,
but should be computable by the methods of Ref. .

Although these strong coupling (and large ) limits 
of transport coefficients, susceptibility, and energy density
cannot be compared with direct field-theoretic calculations,
they may be used as input into the effective hydrodynamic theory
(whose validity is independent of coupling and ).
Inserting the AdS/CFT predictions
(-)
into the result ()
yields the completely explicit form
 
for the spectral density of the stress-stress correlator
in the strong coupling, large  limit.
This correlator is a non-trivial probe of the real-time dynamics
of strongly-coupled supersymmetric Yang-Mills plasma.
Because the AdS/CFT prediction of the supercharge diffusion constant
 is currently lacking, we cannot give an equally explicit result for the
-symmetry current spectral density ().

The result () displays the expected 
relative suppression of the non-analytic part,
and also shows that the ratio of the leading analytic to the
leading non-analytic piece does not depend on
the coupling constant  of the gauge
theory in the strong coupling limit.
In the language of the AdS/CFT correspondence,
, and .



The ten-dimensional gravitational constant  scales as
.
Thus, it is string/supergravity loops,
proportional to , which are responsible for 
corrections in field theory correlators. The corresponding
one-loop amplitudes
are not straightforward to evaluate, given that even the scalar propagator
on the plane-symmetric AdS black hole background is not known analytically.
(
    For progress in this direction,
    see Ref. .) 
However, it would be quite interesting to reproduce hydrodynamic
results like Eq. () directly from supergravity
loop corrections.
Just verifying the form of the small-frequency non-analyticity
from the gravity amplitudes,
without computing the precise coefficient, 
would be a worthwhile goal.

Finally, given that
in various AdS/CFT-like scenarios, finite-temperature field
theories are believed to be exactly equivalent to string
theories on backgrounds with thermal horizons,
it is natural to expect that there must exist a
correspondence between appropriate effective theories as well.
Namely, string theories on thermal
backgrounds should have low-energy descriptions which are dual
to effective long distance descriptions of finite-temperature field
theories, specifically hydrodynamics and kinetic theory
(in weakly coupled regimes).
As we have seen, constructing a
string theory dual of hydrodynamics will necessarily require
incorporating string loop effects in order to reproduce
aspects of long distance dynamics, such as long-time tails,
which are sensitive to the non-linearities of hydrodynamics.





